One of the reasons private enterprise beats socialism of the state-imposed kind is that companies run for profit – as opposed to political reasons, nepotism or just to gouge hapless taxpayers – are efficient. Nowhere is that contrast more stark than in South Africa, where private companies have taken over many of the functions of our crumbling state apparatus. Consumers will vote with their wallets and, in the case of the SA Post Office (Sapo), they have been supporting its competitors for years. The reasons are obvious for anyone who still has to send anything via “snail mail” … a...